pageSummary: I am Simon "Osfrie" Osborne, raising money because they cared for my mother during her cancer fight.
pageSummaryWhat: I am Simon "Osfrie" Osborne, raising money
pageSummaryWhy: they cared for my mother during her cancer fight.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jeni Osborne
story:
December 30th 2009, Jeni Osborne passed away after her 8 year long battle with cancer. Diagnosed with Breast Cancer on September 11th, 2001.

My mother was a kind woman, a teacher in quilting and the best of friends to everyone. Today (06/11/2020) would have been her 64th birthday, so why not raise some money in her name, for those who cared for her so lovingly during her fight so that they can continue to do so for those who still fight for their lives.

Keeping the goal small for now, but this page should be active for the next 5 years so I can come back on mum's birthday and likely on the anniversary of her death and mother's day.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

pageSummary: Holding online fitness classes because I want to help people with cancer live life fully
pageSummaryWhy: I want to help people with cancer live life fully
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Starting Monday 9th of November at 6pm, I will be holding 30 minute fitness classes via zoom. I will be doing this throughout the 2nd lockdown. This will be done every weekday at 6pm. Here is the class timetable:

Monday: - Lower Body Circuits

Tuesday: Upper Body Circuits (you'll need dumbbells, barbells or a TRX)

Wednesday: Lower Body Circuits

Thursday: Upper Body Circuits (you'll need dumbbells, barbells or a TRX)

Friday: Abs Circuits

The suggested donation is £20 (one off! Not a recurring thing!), I understand not everyone has that to give, as long as you've donated something you're welcome to join us for the zoom classes!

Either screenshot your donation and DM me on Instagram: @coachingwithkirt

OR

email me: nandakumarkirthi@gmail.com

And then I will supply you with a health screening form, once the form is submitted, you will get the meeting details.

story:
I'm taking gaming to the next level with Macmillan Game Heroes to help people living with cancer.

This year has been hard enough, but to battle a life threatening illness just makes it worse. 

I have a few friends battling cancer..and sadly I have lost a few friends even distant relatives.

24 hours is going to be a challenge, but one I humbly accept! I may not be able to my help most ways due to covid-19. BUT I can do this.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Eric Warren
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Mom has asked for donations to The British Heart Foundation please if possible. 

Dad's heart troubles meant he wasn't originally expected to reach 45 yet through the skills of Doctors and dedication and love from Mom plus his never give up attitude he had a life we could only have dreamed of at times. Dad made full use of his heart valves, pacemaker, defibrillator and was still active and happy to the end despite his latter years aneurysm. 

Thank you and if you have any queries please just let me know.


Damon

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Tony Rowell
story:
Hi, I’m Ellen and I appreciate you even looking at this page. I sadly lost my grandad last October and he is one of my greatest role models. This challenge is in memory of him - an all round sporting legend whether that be cricket, football, hockey or just a knock around in the garden and a quiet, intelligent, witty  grounded and hard working man whom I aspire to be even half the man of. I’m raising money for cancer research and the British  heart foundation who’s incredible work I’d love to support and especially as my grandad unfortunately faced both cancer and heart issues in his lifetime though never let it hold him back, I remember when I was younger after his triple heart bypass we were playing cricket and he dived for the ball! And how supportive and caring he was, I remember he started watching the FIH pro league (pro hockey matches) on tv so he could understand the rules better and understand the game that me and my family love better. Him and my grandma always tried to come to as many cricket and hockey matches of mine and my sister’s as possible to come and support, even the last time I saw him he came to support at my first match with the 1s for hockey. What a legend! 

I’m also donating money to mind a charity close to my heart supporting people with their mental health. I’m going to split the total raised equally between these 3 charities (The British Heart foundation, Cancer Research and Mind).

For my challenge I’m going to cycle 1,000km (or more!) between my birthday to my grandad’s - from the 2nd December to 13th April.

I know all these issues influence so many people, with 1 in 2 of us getting cancer in our lifetime and 1 in 4 experiencing mental health issues every year. And how it touches many peoples lives, I hope we’re able to continue to be hopeful and have a positive impact on helping others and increasing awareness on these issues.

I am grateful for whatever you’re able to give and if you can’t please share the link if you can!

pageSummaryWhat: Having a birthday dram on my dad
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
As you will know I have a special birthday on Wednesday 11th November. I was going to have a party to celebrate but unfortunately this can’t happen now. Everyone that would have come along would have bought me a couple of drinks,  or knowing me, a few more. What I’m hoping for is that everyone who would have bought me a birthday drink would donate the money to the BHF a charity very very close to our hearts as a family. If it had been for the BHF we wouldn’t have had the past 5 years with my dad. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives.

It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!
title: Hannah's Birthday
Name: Hannah's Birthday

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Wigan fundraising group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community. 

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas!

story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

	Set up your own fundraiser on this page

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs
this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Roxburghshire Fundraising Group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community.

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! 

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas!

We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas

pageSummary: Aika is running for 100 minutes because she wants to raise money to support Guide Dogs
pageSummaryWhy: she wants to raise money to support Guide Dogs
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
100 for Guide Dogs is your challenge, your way. You can choose to Run100, Cycle100 or Swim100 between 1 July and 31 November. However you take on your 100, get sponsored to do it and help us supporting people living with sight loss. 

You could complete 100 metres, 100 minutes, 100 days  be creative!

The sponsorship money you raise will make a difference. £100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.

It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

#TeamGuideDogs

pageSummary: I am raising donations because there are people suffering without a voice.
pageSummaryWhy: there are people suffering without a voice.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The goal of this event is to raise money in support of ALL domestic violence victims who do not have a voice. One of those men is Johnny Depp therefore all moneys raised will go to Great Ormond Street Hospital where Johnny himself donates every year.

Both men and women can be abused yet the mainstream narrative would have us believe that only women can be victims and that an accusation against a man is proof enough to ruin his life. 

ALL victims have an equal right to justice!

The most high profile example of this is actor Johnny Depp who suffered many injuries both physical and psychological allegedly at the hands of his ex-wife Amber Heard.
The injuries he sustained included a severed finger, burns from a cigarette being put out on his face and numerous blows to the head during their marriage.

With the end of their strained relationship in sight Amber desperately filed a restraining order against Johnny accusing him of the very abuse she allegedly inflicted upon him. 
The claims made by Ms. Heard have since been disproven with verified audio and video evidence yet Johnny Depp remains the target of media scrutiny...Why?

This is merely one example of domestic violence. There are thousands of Men and Women suffering through abusive relationships right now in silence.

 Please support those who do not have a voice.
#EnoughIsEnough

pageSummary: We are raising money because It is a charity close to his heart
pageSummaryWhy: It is a charity close to his heart
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Gino Gioia
story:
Our beautiful Gino passed away suddenly on Wednesday 28th October 2020.

Gino was always good at planning an event but not quite following it through.....it was one of the many things we loved about him. He always wanted to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital after his son Raphael was born with a heart condition and received fantastic treatment and support from the staff at Great Ormond Street Hospital.

Instead of cards and flowers we would love for family, friends, colleagues and anyone who was lucky enough to have Gino in their lives to give to this great cause he held close to his heart. 

If you can please leave a message, memory or story of Gino it would be lovely to hear.

Thank you x

story: Follow us on our ultimate socially distanced trek from Bristol all the way to Lapland in time to visit Santa for Christmas! 17 friends, 3,628km, some sore feet and a lot of joy. Between 2nd November and 18th December between us we are aiming to cover the distance to Lapland by walking, jogging or running, stopping off at some landmarks on the way and keeping ourselves warm with good company and good cheer. We’re raising funds for Great Ormond Street Hospital, to help bring some Christmas Magic to poorly children and their families who may not be at home this festive season, and hope you’ll support us on our epic journey!

story:
I will be running 100 miles over 28 days for Cancer Research UK, a charity which funds research into all 200 types of cancer. As the second lock down approached , I was keen to do something to motivate me to make a positive difference in peoples lives. Like many, I found the first lock down tough , I felt as if I was getting myself into bad habits and unhealthy mindsets; contributing negatively on my mental and physical health. Feeling anxious and down, as well as overindulging in takeaways and alcohol. This time round i want it to be different, therefore, I thought there was no better motivation to stay mentally and physically healthy than fundraising for a charity which is close to my heart. Cancer Research has helped improve and save lives of many people including the lives of some of my close family members. Cancer is a sensitive subject for many people and i hope by your donations it could help research progress and one day find a cure to this horrible disease. I think cancer affects us all, whether thats seeing a stranger suffering, a friend, work colleague or a family member. Its something which reminds us that life is valuable and a time where it brings all humans together.

I will be running 25 miles each week over 4 weeks and will be posting updates on here. Thank you for your donations it means a lot - feel free to share my page!

Georgia x

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our school JustGiving page.

At St Joseph’s our mission statement is: ‘Living, Loving and
Learning through Christ’.

This means we are called through the example of Jesus, St Joseph and the teaching of the Catholic Church to help those who are in need or are less fortunate than ourselves. One way we do this is through acts of kindness and charity.

A reported 1 in 2 people will be affected by Cancer at some point in their lives. 

Due to the impact of COVID-19 on our health services, a reported 1 in 3 cancer patients have had their treatment negatively impacted at some point this year.

Fundraising like this will help go towards improving and rebuilding our cancer services to ensure that cancer screening, diagnosis and treatment will not be as severely impacted by future waves of COVID-19.

Each student who completes a 5K effort, whether running, walking or a combination of both will be asked to share this page to friends and family; any donation, no matter the amount, which you can make will be greatly appreciated. 

You can use the child's name who you are sponsoring as the donation name. Feel free to remain anonymous or add your own names to the donation tag.

All students who complete a sponsored 5K will receive a race for life medal to congratulate them in their physical and fund-raising efforts.

Many thanks for your support. 

All at St Joseph's Catholic High School

story:
29th October 1945 - 26th October 2020

Colin was a fun loving, larger than life character who was always up for a laugh. He made an instant impression on everyone he met with his humour and sociable personality.

Unfortunately Colin was diagnosed with oesophagus cancer in early 2020. He put up a strong fight but sadly passed away surrounded by his family at the end of October.

His passing has left a hole in the hearts of all those that were lucky enough to have known and loved him. He will be missed by many and remembered by all for the happy, funny person that he was.

If you wish to make a donation to cancer research in Colin's name it will be greatly appreciated. Every little helps in the fight against this awful disease.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Tony Rowell
story:
Hi, I’m Ellen and I appreciate you even looking at this page. I sadly lost my grandad last October and he is one of my greatest role models. This challenge is in memory of him - an all round sporting legend whether that be cricket, football, hockey or just a knock around in the garden and a quiet, intelligent, witty  grounded and hard working man whom I aspire to be even half the man of. I’m raising money for cancer research and the British  heart foundation who’s incredible work I’d love to support and especially as my grandad unfortunately faced both cancer and heart issues in his lifetime though never let it hold him back, I remember when I was younger after his triple heart bypass we were playing cricket and he dived for the ball! And how supportive and caring he was, I remember he started watching the FIH pro league (pro hockey matches) on tv so he could understand the rules better and understand the game that me and my family love better. Him and my grandma always tried to come to as many cricket and hockey matches of mine and my sister’s as possible to come and support, even the last time I saw him he came to support at my first match with the 1s for hockey. What a legend! 

I’m also donating money to mind a charity close to my heart supporting people with their mental health. I’m going to split the total raised equally between these 3 charities (The British Heart foundation, Cancer Research and Mind).

For my challenge I’m going to cycle 1,000km (or more!) between my birthday to my grandad’s - from the 2nd December to 13th April.

I know all these issues influence so many people, with 1 in 2 of us getting cancer in our lifetime and 1 in 4 experiencing mental health issues every year. And how it touches many peoples lives, I hope we’re able to continue to be hopeful and have a positive impact on helping others and increasing awareness on these issues.

I am grateful for whatever you’re able to give and if you can’t please share the link if you can!

eventName: 28 Day - 300km Challenge in Support of Marie Curie & Prostate Cancer UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Marie Curie provide 'priceless' end of life care and support, caring for over 40,000 terminally ill people in the UK each year.They are there Day & Night providing care & emotional support.

In these unprecedented times all major fundraising events are cancelled or postponed meaning other fundraising support is vital for them to continue providing their invaluable services, so please, please kindly support me in this challenge by making a much appreciated donation. I have given a brief flavour of the challenge below.

Some of you will be aware that I'm another member of the over 50's Lockdown Couch-to-5k Brigade that's now caught the running bug & gaining the mental well-being benefits. Next up was to set myself another challenge with the main goal of raising much needed funds for two charities that have a personal meaning to my family.

The Goal is to cover 300k with 28 days of mixed back to back activities. In total I will Run 50k, Walk 100k and Cycle 150k. This will be broken down into daily activities, Day 1 Run 5k, Day 2 Walk 10k, Day 3 Cycle 15k, then repeat. On the last day of the challenge I will complete the final 30k "Triathlon Style' Walking 10k, Cycling 15k then Running the final 5k.

Completing this Challenge in the Scottish November elements will provide an extra mental hurdle as no rest days, rain hail or shine.

eventName: Can't share cake with the office on your birthday? Make a donation instead
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Our Solihull Hospice has been caring for local people since 1965.

Its a warm and welcoming place where we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones, every day of the year. 

Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by over 200 volunteers  who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.

We have a 24-bed in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish.

Our out-patient unit offers clinics, therapies and group sessions  and freshly cooked lunches made by our chefs. We also support carers and families, including children, with practical advice, counselling and bereavement support groups.

We need to raise £9,600 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Solihull get the care and support they need.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
From the RNLI:

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

From Walk 4 The RNLI:

"Walk 4 The RNLI" aims to raise support for the RNLI. Your donation is going towards a great cause. Thank you.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The RNLI Crowborough Branch is supporting lifeboats in the South East protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. 

Our Crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places in the South east are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

The RNLI relies on donations from the public to continue saving lives at sea, but we haven't been able to fundraise this year and we need your help. 

Thank you for your support.

We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummary: We are cycling 20 miles because we want to protect animals & stop climate change.
pageSummaryWhy: we want to protect animals & stop climate change.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
My name is Alex. I love animals and I like saving up money to stop climate change. I have already done a cake & lemonade sale and a raffle of some of my old toys.

This time, I want to do something bigger to help the environment as much as I can. 20 miles is further than I have ever done so it will be a big challenge! I'm doing it with my Mum and brother and maybe my Dad!

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Name: Ali, Zoe & Oli's cycle for climate!
ProfileWhy: we want to protect animals & stop climate change.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
As part of my Environmental Law project at the University of Westminster, I have decided to hike Ben Nevis, the highest mountain in the U.K., to raise money for WWF. As you may or may not know, we have entered the anthropocene stage of our planetary history, meaning that humans are primarily in control of the environment and climate. I recently visited Iceland and saw first-hand how climate change has impacted our planet and melted our earth’s glaciers. Europe’s largest ice cap by volume – Vatnajokull - has melted 40 sq km each year. Wildlife habitats are being destroyed and we are facing a mass extinction. By the end of the century, polar bears will be wiped out, unless we tackle climate change now. 




This is why myself - Roxanne Spychalski - as well as Kieran Spychalski, Natasha Khan and Danielle Chick have decided that in March we will be tackling the challenge of hiking Ben Nevis. We have decided to choose WWF as our charity to fund because they are an internationally-based charity which focuses on forests, oceans, wildlife, food, climate & energy and water.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Amongst world full of envy, greed, mass distraction are all these kids, and every single of them has a heartbreaking personal story: from Sudan, Yemen, Syria, Ukraine, ....... many many more. 

It should not be this way, ever , for any kids, for mine, for yours, for theirs ....

This is the reason I chose this truly remarkable charity that helps kids worldwide stay safe from danger. 

For all the kids I am going to train at home learn and post videos of me coping various of dance routines for few weeks. 

I am not a dancer, and some dances I may copy well but some will be an embarrassment but I will do my best to entertain you either way.

story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
